<DOC><DOCNO> AP890919-0056 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0614EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-19 0632</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0650</SECOND><HEAD>Hugo Rips Through Eastern Caribbean; Heavy Thunderstorms in West</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Hurricane Hugo headed toward the Bahamas today after itsdevasting 125 mph winds pummeled Puerto Rico, leaving tens ofthousands homeless.   Hurricane warnings were in effect for the southern Bahamas, asHugo packed winds of up to 110 mph early today.   The region's worst storm in a decade skirted Puerto Rico'snorthern coast on Monday and moved northwest.   Forecasters said sophisticated computer projections showed Hugoturning toward the west _ and the U.S. mainland. They urged peoplealong the East Coast from Florida to Virginia to keep track of thehurricane.   Elsewhere, thunderstorms and heavy rains drenched northernCalifornia for a third day, threatening the grape harvest in theregion's wine country. On Monday, more than 2 inches of rain fell atRed Bluff, while an inch and a half fell at Navion.   A snow advisory was in effect this morning for elevations above7,000 feet along the eastern slopes of the Sierra Nevadas ofCalifornia. Up to 6 inches of snow was possible.   In western Nebraska, thunderstorms produced small hail andlocally heavy rain. Showers also were scattered over southernWyoming into northern Utah.   Showers and thunderstorms also fell along the East Coast, fromnortheastern Florida to the mid-Atlantic states. Some drizzle fellover the Northeast.   Record high temperatures for the date Monday were reported inInternational Falls, Minn., with 83 degrees, and Miami, 95 degrees.   The high for the nation on Monday was 99 degrees at Coolidge,Ariz.   Today's forecast called for widespread rain and isolatedthunderstorms from central and southern California through thecentral Plateau and the central Rockies to western South Dakota; andscattered showers and thunderstorms from Florida across the southernand middle Atlantic coast into southern New England.   Highs were expected in the 70s or 80s across much of the nation;in the 60s from the Pacific Northwest across the northern Rockiesinto northern North Dakota, the Great Basin and much of New England;into the low to mid 90s across eastern and southern Texas, thesouthern half of the Florida peninsula and over the desert Southwest.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 29degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 80 degrees at Key West, Fla.,and Phoenix.   Other reports:   _East: Albany, N.Y., 55 partly cloudy; Atlanta 64 fair; Boston 60drizzle; Buffalo 53 fair; Charleston, S.C., 69 cloudy; Chattanooga60 fair; Cincinnati 57 fair; Cleveland 54 fair; Detroit 56 foggy;Hatteras 71 rain; Jacksonville 70 fair; Key West 80 partly cloudy;Macon 66 partly cloudy; Miami 74 partly cloudy; New York 63 cloudy;Philadelphia 65 showery; Pittsburgh 54 foggy; Portland, Maine, 57cloudy; Richmond 66 rain; Tampa 72 fair; Washington, D.C., 68 windy.   _Central: Birmingham 63 fair; Bismarck 55 fair; Chicago 59 fair;Denver 57 fair; Des Moines 59 foggy; Fort Worth 63 fair;Indianapolis 55 fair; Kansas City 61 fair; Little Rock 58 fair;Louisville 59 fair; Nashville 59 fair; New Orleans 73 fair; NorthPlatte 66 fair; Oklahoma City 60 fair; Omaha 65 fair; Rapid City 55rain; St. Louis 62 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 67 partly cloudy;Sault Ste. Marie 55 foggy; San Antonio 69 fair.   _West: Albuquerque 69 fair; Anchorage 40 fair; Boise 44 fair;Casper 53 showery; Fairbanks 39 fair; Great Falls 45 fair; Honolulu78 partly cloudy; Las Vegas 64 fair; Los Angeles 63 partly cloudy;Medford 49 fair; Pendleton 49 fair; Portland, Ore., 56 fair; Reno 47showery; Salt Lake City 54 fair; San Diego 65 partly cloudy; SanFrancisco 52 fair; Seattle 53 fair; Spokane 49 cloudy.   _International: Calgary 41 fair; Montreal 55 foggy; Ottawa 54foggy; Regina 45 foggy; Toronto 50 fair; Winnipeg 52 cloudy; MexicoCity 57 cloudy; Merida 75 foggy; Nassau 79 partly cloudy.</TEXT></DOC>